</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ujeshuah.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Jeshuah</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(3/9/02 12:14:37 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=23.topic&index=52>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Whats the purpose of the 66% nerf</span><hr size=1> Well, I feel the 66% nerf should be changed to this:<br>
<br>
66% of nuke dmg vs. Int classes<br>
86% of nuke dmg vs. Priest classes/bard/ranger/rogue<br>
100% of nuke dmg vs. Sk/Warrior/Paladin<br>
<br>
<br>
Yes I'm sure most people would disagree with this, but allow me to have a moment to defend this:  <br>
<br>
The melee classes, as not only the masters of melee damage, are also the masters of melee defence (ac).  The casting classes, aside from a cleric and shaman, don't even come close to the ac of melees.  Int casters are the most suceptible to melee damage, in addition to having the least hp, on average.<br>
<br>
Nuke defence is not quite as clear cut.  To defend against nukes someone needs high fire/cold/magic resists, which absolutely any class can get.  Honestly, I think resists on most classes are very balanced (I probably said otherwise before, but oh well).  Resist gear like blue diamond gear can be worn by anyone, so is getting resists high for most really an issue?<br>
<br>
So, lets assume you believe most people can get near to the same *high* resists on a pvp server, let me tell you about nukes damage vs high resists--its pathetic.  I almost always get partial resists on my draughts, my most commonly used nuke.  When a 66% nerf is cut down even more to a partial resist, the nuke ends up being like 50-200hp much of the time.  Since I am a wizard, I have the option of using a lure, but at a very high casting time and a high mana cost--but then again, that's fair since I don't have high hp/ac, a pet, can't heal, or rapture, right?  So when talkng about the best defence vs. nukes, the classes with the most hp and ease of healing have the best defence.<br>
<br>
OK, so to recap so far ... melees have the best defence to melee damage, and tanks/priests have the best defence to nuke damage due to high hp/healing ability.  Wouldn't it make sense that since melees, esp. tanks, have the best defence against melee damage in pvp; int casters should have the best defence against nuke damage?<br>
<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/uaerimusshadowborn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Aerimus Shadowborn</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(3/9/02 4:44:53 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm27.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=23.topic&index=53>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Whats the purpose of the 66% nerf</span><hr size=1> As posted earlier.<br>
<br>
My suggestion for spell dmg percentage tables...<br>
<br>
It goes as follows. Each class gets a series of table based on lvl range. The level ranges for int casters would be...<br>
<br>
1-19, 20-28, 29-38, 39-48, 49-54, 55-60<br>
<br>
priest classes would be slightly different<br>
<br>
Each table would look like this...<br>
<br>
Wiz 1-19 Table<br>
Dmg vs wizards x% of full dmg in pvp<br>
Dmg vs enchanters x% of full dmg in pvp<br>
Dmg vs mages x% of full dmg in pvp<br>
Dmg vs necromancers x% of full dmg in pvp<br>
Dmg vs warriors x% of full dmg in pvp<br>
Dmg vs rogues x% of full dmg in pvp<br>
Dmg vs monks x% of full dmg in pvp<br>
Dmg vs rangers x% of full dmg in pvp<br>
Dmg vs paladins x% of full dmg in pvp<br>
Dmg vs beastlords x% of full dmg in pvp<br>
Dmg vs shadow knights x% of full dmg in pvp<br>
Dmg vs bards x% of full dmg in pvp<br>
Dmg vs druids x% of full dmg in pvp<br>
Dmg vs shaman x% of full dmg in pvp<br>
Dmg vs clerics x% of full dmg in pvp<br>
<br>
This would allow them to precisely tune dmg rather than just nerfing it to 66%. <br>
<br>
In addition I think individual spells should have 3 new attributes.<br>
<br>
A) pvp dmg modifier so that single spells could be tuned to be stronger or weaker when used on players. A spell with a 1.5 modifier when used in a situation with 66% spell dmg as per the tables above would do the full listed dmg - resists.<br>
<br>
B) pvp resist modifier to give players more or less chance to resist the spell, I believe there is allready a general attribute that is similar but that it effects both pvp and pve which doesn't allow accurate tuning for pvp.<br>
<br>
C) set resist lvl modifier to be used in place of attribute B for some 50+ spells that would set the base lvl of resist for a spell. In other words the 54 druid nuke scorae might always hit as if the target has x lvl of resist. X being a number that is fair for all parties.<br>
<br>
I'm thinking C might be reserved for lvl 60 spells and it would have to use either the given level of resist for that spell or the players resist whichever was lower.<br>
<br>
Examples...<br>
<br>
60 mage nukes a rogue with shock of fiery blades, base dmg is 1005 dmg.  modifier vs roguemight be 66% so the spell does 663 dmg the spell itself may have a -5% so you get 630 dmg this is then checked against resisting.  Since it is a 60 spell it has a base resist lvl as described above say its 100.  It will be checked against 100 fire resist unless the rogue has less than 100 in which case the lesser number will be used.<br>
<br>
A 60 wizard nukes a sk with garrisions superior sundering, base dmg is 2100, modifier vs sk might be 100% so dmg is 2100, the spell itself may have a +10% modifier so dmg is 2310. Since it is a 60 spell it has a base resist lvl as described above say its 100.  It will be checked against 100 fire resist unless the sk has less than 100 in which case the lesser number will be used.<br>
<br>
Do not take the -10% modifier or the +10% modifier to mean I favor buffing or nerfing those specific spells in pvp  That was only an example. <br>
<br>
In general I would favor giving a greater than 66% modifier mainly to the 55-60 tables and largely to nukers hitting classes with high high hp or healing power.  Specific spell modifiers that would be calculated after the base reduction by class would require a lot of testing and discussion I imagine.<br>
<br>
This set of suggestions is a much better solution than messing around with the modifier for resist debuffs in pvp helping some spells to much some to little.<br>
<br>
The second attribute even adresses an enchanter concern with NOTHING landing. If spells had attribute B certain spells could be given inherently less resistance when used in pvp without making them more powerful in pve or raising the pvp resisted debuff modifier (currently all resistance debuffs do 1.5 normal when used in pvp) to such a ridiculous extent that enc end up blinding, rooting, and owning people.<br>
<br>
In addition the first attribute would provide a clean way to remove mannaburn from the pvp environment as verant has stated is neccesary. Simply set attribute A to 0% of full dmg in pvp.<br>
<br>
